{"nodes":[{"label":"Richard Russell Jr.","x":-374.6158752441406,"y":-197.69760131835938,"id":"5","attributes":{"Info":"President pro tempore of the Senate during the first Nixon administration. Russell was \"best known for his efforts to oppose civil rights legislation (georgiaencyclopedia.org).\""},"color":"rgb(223,242,242)","size":52.75},{"label":"Spiro Agnew","x":-109.40475463867188,"y":-18.34588623046875,"id":"6","attributes":{"Info":"Vice President and Senate President during the Nixon administration."},"color":"rgb(223,242,242)","size":52.75},{"label":"Dana L. Farnsworth, MD","x":113.63053894042969,"y":1189.136474609375,"id":"16","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be Vice Chairman of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"John A. Howard, PhD","x":858.6539916992188,"y":1183.098388671875,"id":"21","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"John Ehrlichman","x":-827.4151000976562,"y":-774.3218383789062,"id":"2","attributes":{"Info":"Chief Domestic Advisor to President Nixon."},"color":"rgb(183,226,216)","size":76.0},{"label":"Michael R. Sonnenreich","x":1333.515869140625,"y":1107.8416748046875,"id":"28","attributes":{"Info":"Executive Director of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(71,168,128)","size":60.0},{"label":"91st U.S. Congress","x":978.608642578125,"y":-653.4235229492188,"id":"13","attributes":{"Info":"Enacted the Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970 during Nixon\u0027s presidency."},"color":"rgb(223,141,47)","size":107.0},{"label":"Harold E. Hughes","x":1053.783203125,"y":-46.84626770019531,"id":"22","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Congressional leadership to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse and a U.S. Senator from Iowa (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"Executive Office of the President","x":-867.6738891601562,"y":-310.88861083984375,"id":"15","attributes":{"Info":""},"color":"rgb(243,149,58)","size":60.5},{"label":"Harley O. Staggers","x":301.89935302734375,"y":-702.3402099609375,"id":"8","attributes":{"Info":"Democratic U.S. Representative from West Virginia who introduced the Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970 in the House. Staggers\u0027 primary legislative concern was with the deregulation of railroads (reform.democrats.house.gov)."},"color":"rgb(223,242,242)","size":52.75},{"label":"Tim Lee Carter","x":691.1586303710938,"y":177.84548950195312,"id":"18","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Congressional leadership to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse and a U.S. Representative from Kentucky (medicalmarijuana.procon.org). Defended Nixon during his impeachment hearings (apnewsarchive.com). "},"color":"rgb(51,151,104)","size":60.0},{"label":"Charles 0. Galvin, SJD","x":447.6505126953125,"y":1034.589111328125,"id":"20","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"Maurice H. Seevers, MD, PhD","x":195.07589721679688,"y":327.9636535644531,"id":"25","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"J. Thomas Ungerleider, MD","x":534.1578979492188,"y":804.8146362304688,"id":"26","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"Joan Ganz Cooney","x":261.54644775390625,"y":545.1263427734375,"id":"19","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"Raymond Shafer","x":-290.91363525390625,"y":506.9490661621094,"id":"9","attributes":{"Info":"Governor of Pennsylvania who was personally appointed by President Nixon to chair the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org). Dubbed the \"Shafer Commission,\" the committee produced a report calling for the decriminalization of marijuana, against the wishes of President Nixon, who, prior to the release of the Commission\u0027s report, warned Shafer that \"You\u0027re enough of a pro to know that for you to come out with something that would run counter to what Congress feels ... and what we\u0027re planning to do would make your commission just look bad as hell (norml.org).\""},"color":"rgb(51,151,104)","size":161.25},{"label":"Jacob K. Javits","x":1402.049560546875,"y":498.7315979003906,"id":"23","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Congressional leadership to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse and a U.S. Senator from New York (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"Paul G. Rogers","x":1227.10986328125,"y":312.6499938964844,"id":"24","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Congressional leadership to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse and a U.S. Representative from Florida (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"Roger O. Egeberg","x":-274.7889099121094,"y":-730.9927368164062,"id":"7","attributes":{"Info":"Assistant Secretary for Health and Scientific Affairs in the Department of Health, Education, and Welfare during the Nixon administration (nytimes.com). While the Controlled Substances Act was being drafted, Egeberg wrote to Harley O. Staggers that marijuana be temporarily be placed in the most restrictive category of drugs, Schedule I (US National Library of Medicine)."},"color":"rgb(223,242,242)","size":52.75},{"label":"Dan Baum","x":-558.407958984375,"y":-1013.3302612304688,"id":"4","attributes":{"Info":"Journalist who interviewed John Ehrlichman in 1994, during which Ehrlichman reportedly told Baum: \"We knew we couldn\u0027t make it illegal to be either against the war or black, but by getting the public to associate the hippies with marijuana and blacks with heroin. And then criminalizing both heavily, we could disrupt those communities. We could arrest their leaders. raid their homes, break up their meetings, and vilify them night after night on the evening news. Did we know we were lying about the drugs? Of course we did (harpers.org).\""},"color":"rgb(237,248,251)","size":45.0},{"label":"\"Silent Majority\"","x":-1355.731201171875,"y":686.2410278320312,"id":"29","attributes":{"Info":"Nixon�s �Silent Majority� was made up of politically inactive middle class rural and suburban white blue-collar workers who felt that their traditional American values were being attacked. Those in the �Silent Majority� were not all politically conservative, but what they had in common was they all felt threatened by the social changes that were underway during the 60�s. "},"color":"rgb(237,248,251)","size":120.0},{"label":"Drug Enforcement Agency","x":-938.20166015625,"y":1004.3172607421875,"id":"12","attributes":{"Info":"Established by President Nixon (resources.learningforlife.org)."},"color":"rgb(250,152,63)","size":45.0},{"label":"H.R. Haldeman","x":-1275.308837890625,"y":-423.6278991699219,"id":"3","attributes":{"Info":"White House Chief of Staff during the Nixon administration. Recorded daily diary entries that were later published, one of which said, referring to President Nixon as \u0027P\u0027: \"P emphasized that you have to face the fact that the whole problem is really the blacks. The key is to devise a system that recognizes this while not appearing to (nytimes.com).\""},"color":"rgb(210,237,233)","size":60.5},{"label":"James O. Eastland","x":-438.67034912109375,"y":-482.53289794921875,"id":"10","attributes":{"Info":"Old personal friend of President Nixon, who helped Eastland in his re-election campaign to Senate. Eastland was the President pro tempore of the Senate during the second Nixon administration. Two years after the Shafer Commission\u0027s report was published, Eastland and a subcommittee he led released a report claiming that marijuana posed a significant danger to society, the opposite of the Shafer Commission\u0027s findings (archive.org). Eastland was well known for his opposition to civil rights (mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us)."},"color":"rgb(237,248,251)","size":45.0},{"label":"Nelson Rockefeller","x":-729.0497436523438,"y":649.2664794921875,"id":"11","attributes":{"Info":"Governor of New York who passed the Rockefeller Drug Laws, the harshest drug laws in the nation, 2 years after President Nixon declared the War on Drugs (npr.org). Rockefeller had presidential aspirations and wanted to appear less liberal and more \"tough on crime\" in order to appeal to voters. "},"color":"rgb(223,242,242)","size":52.75},{"label":"Richard Nixon","x":-1221.782470703125,"y":122.35310363769531,"id":"1","attributes":{"Info":"President of the United States from 1969 to 1974, during which he declared the War on Drugs in a special message to Congress (presidency.ucsb.edu). Was well known to look negatively upon American Jews, Italian Americans, Irish Americans, and African Americans (nytimes.com)."},"color":"rgb(0,109,44)","size":230.0},{"label":"Henry Brill, MD","x":1069.76318359375,"y":961.847412109375,"id":"17","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0},{"label":"National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse","x":949.42724609375,"y":633.8389282226562,"id":"14","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by President Nixon to investigate the effects of marijuana and other drugs and make recommendations. Ultimately released a report advising the decriminalization of marijuana, which the White House ignored (medicalmarijuana.procon.org). "},"color":"rgb(205,129,28)","size":161.25},{"label":"Mitchell Ware, JD","x":94.66751861572266,"y":916.9913940429688,"id":"27","attributes":{"Info":"Appointed by Nixon to be a member of the National Commission on Marihuana and Drug Abuse (medicalmarijuana.procon.org)."},"color":"rgb(61,160,116)","size":60.0}],"edges":[{"source":"24","target":"18","id":"145","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"27","target":"25","id":"219","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"1","target":"5","id":"5","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"28","target":"26","id":"246","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"19","target":"14","id":"74","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"27","target":"14","id":"209","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"14","target":"1","id":"27","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"21","target":"28","id":"255","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"20","target":"22","id":"118","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"17","target":"24","id":"155","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"25","target":"28","id":"259","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"19","target":"1","id":"274","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"23","target":"14","id":"122","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"19","target":"25","id":"178","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"1","target":"19","id":"266","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"20","target":"19","id":"81","attributes":{},"color":"rgb(0,0,0)","size":1.0},{"source":"9","target":"19","id":"57","attributes